CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, National Edition, August 8, 1942, pg. 1, reads: "Officers Charge Army Medics To "Conserve Fighting Strength" - Immediately after the 19 new Army doctors had received their certificates from Field Service school at Carlisle Barracks, Pa., qualifying them for active combat duty with regular troops, the Courier photographer snapped this picture. Shown, left to right are, First Lieutenants James D. Phillip, Harrisburg, Pa.; Ernest Williams, Buffalo, N.Y.; George J. Thomas Jr., Winston Salem, N.C.; Joseph J. Quarles, Norfolk, Va.; Roscoe C. Williams, Annemarie, Ala.; Claude G. Walker, Washington, D.C.; Bruce P. McDonald, Sumpter, S.C.; Arnold H. Maloney, Jr., Washington, D.C.; T.M. Campbell, Jr., Tuskegee, Ala.; James C. Gray, Washington, D.C.; Edmund F. Noel, Jackson, Miss.; Stanis S. Melendez, Jr., Pittsburgh, Pa.; John W. Moore, Jr., LaGrange, Ga.; Edwin A. Lee, Indianola, Miss.; C.E. Morgan, Aiken S.C.; Thomas W. Harris, Annapolis, Md.; A.C. Johnson, Atlanta, Ga.; Warren W. Schell, Jr., Jacksonville, Fla., and William J. Reden, Tampa, Fla. - Harris photo."
TitMainTitle: Group portrait of U. S. Army doctors, from left: James D. Phillip, Ernest Williams, George J. Thomas Jr., Joseph J. Quarles, Roscoe C. Williams, Claude G. Walker, Bruce P. McDonald, Arnold H. Maloney Jr., T. M. Campbell Jr., James C. Gray,  Edmund F. Noel, Stanis S. Melendez Jr., John W. Moore Jr., Edwin A. Lee, C. E. Morgan, Thomas W. Harris, A. C. Johnson, Warren W. Schell Jr., and William J. Reden, standing in line at Field Service school at Carlisle Barracks, Pennsylvania
